[1] Michigan
Date: Mon 18 Dec 2017 6:56 PM EST
Source: TV6, Upper Michigan's Source, WLUC [edited]
http://www.uppermichiganssource.com/content/news/Six-cases-of-Pertussis-are-confirmed-in-Marquette-County-463999573.html


The 6 cases of pertussis confirmed in Marquette county is cause for concern. The Marquette County Health Department [MCHS] said this bacterial illness, known as whooping cough, is preventable through vaccines. However officials said it is hard to contain because the illness is spread without knowing one has it. Symptoms include congestion and violent coughing. The illness is treatable through antibiotics making it less contagious, but the coughing can last for months.

Although whooping cough is mostly found in schools, the MCHS is warning the county to be aware of symptoms. "But the whole community needs to think about this because kids travel for sports events and those kinds of things so it's a good time to again double check to make sure your family is vaccinated," said Dr Terry Frankovich, the medical director.

[byline: Nicole Buchmann]

