[2] California
Date: Tue 19 Dec 2017 5:39 am PST
Source: East Bay Times [edited]
https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2017/12/19/whooping-cough-strikes-east-bay-high-school/


Whooping cough has sickened a hand full of students at Foothill High School -- a reminder that the once rare respiratory disease in California has made a comeback in the past 8 years.

School officials confirmed this week that a "single digit" number of Foothill students are believed to have contracted the highly contagious respiratory disease, also called pertussis. The symptoms start out like a common cold but can transform in serious cases to fits of coughing and a whooping sound while gasping for air.

Pleasanton school officials said they are declining to disclose the exact number of cases because county health officials think doing so would make it easier for the public to identify the infected individuals. In all of Alameda county, there have been 98 pertussis cases so far this year [2017], and there were 77 cases in 2016, according to county and state public health departments.

On [14 Dec 2017], the Pleasanton school system finished emailing notices about whooping cough to families of students in the Foothill classes with a student suspected of being infected, said spokesman Patrick Gannon. The message told the families that students may have been exposed to the bacterial disease and should take steps to minimize the risk and monitor for symptoms, he said.

Protective measures include people getting vaccinations and covering noses and mouths when coughing or sneezing to prevent the spreading of droplets with the contagious bacteria, health officials said.

Whooping cough had been relatively rare in California until an outbreak in 2010, when there were more than 9447 cases with 10 deaths, the most in 65 years in the state. Other states also reported a surge that year. In California, the number of cases declined after 2010, but surged again to 11 203 cases in 2014 with 365 of them in Alameda county, state health officials reported. As of [3 Dec 2017], California has reported 2084 cases. Alameda county has had 98 cases so far this year, according to Alameda County Public Health Department.

Scientists and medical experts have suggested the increase in cases may be related to fewer parents vaccinating their children, and the effectiveness of the vaccines wearing off in youngsters as they reach their early teen years. Particularly vulnerable are high school students who have only received acellular pertussis vaccines even if they received a so-called Tdap booster before they were in the 7th grade, according to the state Department of Public Health.

Pertussis cases also appear to rise and drop in cycles that last from 3 to 5 years, health officials added.

[byline: Denis Cuff]

