[3] North Carolina
Date: Wed 20 Dec 2017 12:16 PM EST
Source: BlueRidge Now, Time-News Online [edited]
http://www.blueridgenow.com/news/20171220/whooping-cough-cases-at-56-what-you-need-to-know


According to Thursday's report [21 Dec 2017] from the health department, 56 cases have now been identified.

Cases of whooping cough, or pertussis, continue to climb in Henderson county. As school is out for the holidays and families get together to celebrate, health officials are keeping a close eye on the outbreak, now at 52 cases.

The outbreak, spread across a majority of county schools but also found in the community, has raised questions since the first cases appeared at the end of November [2017].

Kim Horton, communications specialist with the Henderson County Department of Public Health, says that one check in the win column is that there have been no cases resulting in death or patients entering the intensive care unit.

Students in Henderson county are required to take the vaccine to attend school, unless a religious or medical exemption is made, and again before entering the 7th grade. The majority of cases in the county have been found in people who have been vaccinated. Those who have had the vaccine can still get whooping cough, but will have milder symptoms.

Horton said the vaccine itself, modified to be less potent several years ago because of some severe side effects, is one of waning immunity. Pertussis is classified as a vaccine-modified disease instead of a vaccine-prevented disease.

[byline: Derek Lacey]

