[5] New Zealand (Gisborne)
Date: Sat 30 Dec 2017 8:32 AM NZDT
Source: Gisborne Herald [edited]
http://gisborneherald.co.nz/localnews/3160090-135/whooping-cough-on-the-rise


[A mother] is relieved her daughter is getting better after contracting whooping cough. Health officials warn people to watch out for the disease, after a rise in the number of people with it here and in other areas. Hauora Tairawhiti medical officer of health Margot McLean says New Zealand is in the early stages of a whooping cough epidemic. The best celebration [for the mother] this new year will be enjoying the good health of her baby daughter, who has spent 3 of her 8 weeks of life battling whooping cough. Before Christmas, she was admitted to Planet Sunshine at Gisborne Hospital, where the frightening coughing fits finally started to subside. [The baby] is her 1st child. "Watching my baby struggling to breathe, her lips blue and her face turning pink, then purple, is terrifying. I wouldn't wish this on anyone. "When she coughed she would choke. The nurses showed me how to sit her up and rub her back. If that didn't work, I would blow on her face. I couldn't leave her side and I was worried when I fell asleep."

[The mother an her baby] are not alone, says Margot McLean. New Zealand is in the early stages of a whooping cough epidemic and other areas have also seen a rise in cases. "In the past 2 weeks, 2 babies have been admitted to Gisborne Hospital with whooping cough."

Whooping cough causes prolonged bouts of coughing that can end in vomiting or breathlessness. "It can be very serious, especially for those under one." The best prevention is immunisation. "Pregnant mums should get their free immunisation between 28 and 38 weeks of pregnancy. Babies receive their 1st free immunisation at 6 weeks, 3 months, and 5 months. Don't delay with vaccinations, as young babies are the most at risk and need to get their protection as soon as possible."

Dr McLean says [the mother] did the right thing. She was immunised while pregnant, giving [her baby] some protection through the shared bloodstream. This might have prevented [her baby] becoming more unwell when she contracted whooping cough at five weeks, just before her first vaccination.

Whooping cough spreads through coughing and sneezing. People with whooping cough are infectious from 6 days after exposure to the bacteria, when symptoms are like a normal cold, to 3 weeks after the ''whooping'' cough begins, unless treated with antibiotics. Dr McLean says many babies catch whooping cough from older siblings or parents, often before they are old enough to be vaccinated. "That is why staff from maternity, neonatal and Planet Sunshine teams at Gisborne Hospital are all immunised. If babies catch whooping cough, they might not be able to feed or breathe properly, become so ill they need to go to hospital, and could end up with complications such as pneumonia and brain damage."

Anyone with a cough that does not go away should avoid contact with babies and young children, and get advice from a health professional or from Healthline 0800 611 116.

